@jarben Yes I can implement it using `visualMap` like this: (although the emphasis setting seems to be a little ugly)

```js
option = {
    "color": [
        "#2196f3",
        "#e91e63"
    ],
    visualMap: {
        type: 'piecewise',
        dimension: 1,
        top: 0,
        left: 'center',
        orient: 'horizontal',
        categories: ['Category 1', 'Category 2'],
        hoverLink: false,
        inRange: {
            color: {
                "Category 1": "#2196f3",
                "Category 2": "#e91e63"
            }
        }
    },
    "series": [
        {
            "map": "world",
            "name": "Category 1",
            "type": "map",
            "scaleLimit": {
                "min": 10
            },
            "center": [
                "5",
                "50"
            ],
            "data": [
                {
                    "name": "United Kingdom",
                    "value": [6, "Category 1"],
                    "itemStyle": {
                        "emphasis": {
                            "areaColor": "rgb(81, 173, 246)"
                        }
                    },                    
                },
                {
                    "name": "Czech Republic",
                    "value": [5, "Category 2"],
                    "itemStyle": {
                        "emphasis": {
                            "areaColor": "rgb(238, 76, 131)"
                        }
                    }                    
                }                
            ]
        }
    ]
}
```

From the snippet code you provided, I guess you miss the setting `yAxisIndex: 1` in series.
```js
series: [{
    ...,
}, {
    ...,
    yAxisIndex: 1
}]
```

If my guess is not correct, could you provide the full `echarts option` to let us understand what do you expect actually?

About question 1,  yes you can put different categories in different series respectively, like, 

```js
option = {
    legend: {
        data: ['category 0', 'category 1']
    },
    series: [{
        name: 'category 0',
        type: 'parallel',
        data: data0
    }, {
        name: 'category 1',
        type: 'parallel',
        data: data1
    }]
}
```

About question 2, you've mentioned 
> pass the time values like a 'timeline' rather than string

But sorry I am not sure what `'timeline'` exactly is, could explain it in detail?
In category axis (`axis.type` is `'category'`), only string value can be accepted.
In time axis (`axis.type` is `'time'`), both time string (like `'2012-12-12'`), JavaScript Date Object, or timestamp (like 1486563839702) can be accepted.

